Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The mode of transmission of EHD in nature is via a _Culicoides_ sp.
biting fly or midge. _Culicoides variipennis_ is the most commonly
incriminated vector in North America. A common observation in
outbreaks involving large numbers of deer is that they are single
epizootics, which do not usually recur. Die-offs involving small
numbers of deer occur almost annually, and the disease appears to be
enzootic in these areas. All documented outbreaks of EHD have occurred
during late summer and early fall (August-October, being somewhat
location dependant) and have ceased abruptly with the onset of frost.

For a more detailed review of EHD readers are encouraged to see
ProMED-mail post 20100819.2880. - Mod.TG]

[The state of Michigan in the Great Lakes Region of the US can be
